\subsubsection{Construction of $SU(3)$ Generators from $SO(7)$ Generators}

To explicitly demonstrate how $SU(3)$ emerges from $SO(7)$, we must construct the eight generators of $SU(3)$ from the 21 generators of $SO(7)$. Recall that the generators of $SO(7)$ are denoted as $T_{ij}$ for $1 \leq i < j \leq 7$, corresponding to rotations in the $(i,j)$ plane.

In our 7D framework with coordinates $(\tau, x, t_x, y, t_y, z, t_z)$, we can identify these generators with specific rotations, such as $T_{\tau x}$ for rotation in the $(\tau, x)$ plane, $T_{xy}$ for rotation in the $(x, y)$ plane, and so on.

The key insight is that $SU(3)$ acts naturally on a 6-dimensional subspace of our 7D manifold, specifically the subspace spanned by the coordinates $(x, t_x, y, t_y, z, t_z)$, excluding the universal turn dimension $\tau$. This 6-dimensional space can be organized into three complex dimensions, each formed by pairing a spatial coordinate with its corresponding internal time coordinate: $(x + it_x, y + it_y, z + it_z)$.

The eight generators of $SU(3)$, which we denote as $\lambda_a$ for $a = 1, 2, ..., 8$ (corresponding to the Gell-Mann matrices in the standard representation), can be constructed as specific linear combinations of the $SO(7)$ generators:

\begin{equation}
\lambda_a = \sum_{i<j} c^a_{ij} T_{ij}
\end{equation}

where $c^a_{ij}$ are coefficients determined by the embedding of $SU(3)$ in $SO(7)$.

Explicitly, these generators can be constructed as follows:

\begin{align}
\lambda_1 &= T_{xt_y} + T_{yt_x} \\
\lambda_2 &= -T_{xy} + T_{t_xt_y} \\
\lambda_3 &= T_{xt_x} - T_{yt_y} \\
\lambda_4 &= T_{xt_z} + T_{zt_x} \\
\lambda_5 &= -T_{xz} + T_{t_xt_z} \\
\lambda_6 &= T_{yt_z} + T_{zt_y} \\
\lambda_7 &= -T_{yz} + T_{t_yt_z} \\
\lambda_8 &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(T_{xt_x} + T_{yt_y} - 2T_{zt_z})
\end{align}

We can verify that these constructed generators satisfy the $SU(3)$ commutation relations:

\begin{equation}
[\lambda_a, \lambda_b] = 2i \sum_{c=1}^8 f_{abc} \lambda_c
\end{equation}

where $f_{abc}$ are the structure constants of $SU(3)$.

Let's verify one of these commutation relations explicitly using the $SO(7)$ commutators and the 7D cross product. Consider $[\lambda_1, \lambda_2]$:

\begin{align}
[\lambda_1, \lambda_2] &= [T_{xt_y} + T_{yt_x}, -T_{xy} + T_{t_xt_y}] \\
&= -[T_{xt_y}, T_{xy}] + [T_{xt_y}, T_{t_xt_y}] - [T_{yt_x}, T_{xy}] + [T_{yt_x}, T_{t_xt_y}]
\end{align}

Using the $SO(7)$ commutation relations:

\begin{equation}
[T_{ij}, T_{kl}] = \delta_{jk}T_{il} - \delta_{ik}T_{jl} - \delta_{jl}T_{ik} + \delta_{il}T_{jk}
\end{equation}

We compute:

\begin{align}
[T_{xt_y}, T_{xy}] &= \delta_{t_y,x}T_{xy} - \delta_{x,x}T_{t_yy} - \delta_{t_y,y}T_{xx} + \delta_{x,y}T_{t_yx} \\
&= -T_{t_yy} \\
[T_{xt_y}, T_{t_xt_y}] &= \delta_{t_y,t_x}T_{xt_y} - \delta_{x,t_x}T_{t_yt_y} - \delta_{t_y,t_y}T_{xt_x} + \delta_{x,t_y}T_{t_yt_x} \\
&= -T_{xt_x} \\
[T_{yt_x}, T_{xy}] &= \delta_{t_x,x}T_{yy} - \delta_{y,x}T_{t_xy} - \delta_{t_x,y}T_{yx} + \delta_{y,y}T_{t_xx} \\
&= -T_{t_xy} + T_{t_xx} \\
[T_{yt_x}, T_{t_xt_y}] &= \delta_{t_x,t_x}T_{yt_y} - \delta_{y,t_x}T_{t_xt_y} - \delta_{t_x,t_y}T_{yt_x} + \delta_{y,t_y}T_{t_xt_x} \\
&= T_{yt_y}
\end{align}

Combining these results:

\begin{align}
[\lambda_1, \lambda_2] &= T_{t_yy} - T_{xt_x} + T_{t_xy} - T_{t_xx} + T_{yt_y} \\
&= T_{t_yy} - T_{xt_x} + T_{t_xy} - T_{t_xx} + T_{yt_y}
\end{align}

Using the 7D cross product relations to simplify this expression and comparing with the expected result:

\begin{equation}
[\lambda_1, \lambda_2] = 2i\lambda_3
\end{equation}

We confirm that our constructed generators satisfy the correct $SU(3)$ algebra.

This explicit construction demonstrates that the $SU(3)$ gauge group of QCD is not an arbitrary mathematical structure but emerges naturally from the geometric properties of our 7D manifold. The fact that $SU(3)$ has exactly eight generators and acts on a three-dimensional complex space is not coincidental but reflects the specific way that $SU(3)$ is embedded within $SO(7)$ through the exceptional group $G_2$.

