\subsection{Color Charge and Quark Fields in the 7D Framework}

\subsubsection{Geometric Origin of Color}

In conventional QCD, color is introduced as an internal quantum number with three possible values (red, green, blue), assigned to quarks to ensure that they transform in the fundamental representation of $SU(3)$. While mathematically consistent, this approach provides limited insight into the physical meaning of color or why nature should choose precisely three colors.

