\begin{align}
|\bar{r}\rangle &\sim (x - it_x, 0, 0) \\
|\bar{g}\rangle &\sim (0, y - it_y, 0) \\
|\bar{b}\rangle &\sim (0, 0, z - it_z)
\end{align}

These states form a basis for the anti-fundamental (conjugate) representation of $SU(3)$.

Color-neutral states correspond to configurations that are invariant under $SU(3)$ transformations. The simplest examples are the quark-antiquark combinations (mesons) and the three-quark combinations (baryons) that form singlet representations of $SU(3)$.

This geometric interpretation of color provides a natural explanation for why quarks must combine to form color-neutral states, as we will explore further in our discussion of confinement.

